   {:e #blake3 "7e220a2946500b2385b2426e9ee39f7a070562e975d8b70ca8f1c40d2bec6b85" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "DESIGN: Lateral Scan — the third direction of the bilateral loop. Forward (spec→impl), Backward (impl→spec), Lateral (impl→entry). Detects phantom witnesses: tests that pass on unreachable code. Integration: subtract phantom witness count from F(S).validation, making the fitness function honest. Uses the same graph reachability infrastructure as the topology pipeline (DiGraph + BFS from query/graph.rs). The lateral scan completes the verification chain across ALL four boundaries: Intent→Spec→Impl→Behavior. Axiologically aligned: DDIS must never claim more coherence than exists. Phantom witnesses inflate F(S), violating this commitment. The lateral scan restores honesty.; Lateral Composition Integrity; BOUNDARY FRAMEWORK: 6 spec elements (3 INV, 2 ADR, 2 NEG) + 11 tasks (1 EPIC + 10 implementation) fully specified with dependency graph. Dependency chain: BOUNDARY-1 (trait) -> [BOUNDARY-2 (registry) || BOUNDARY-3 (refactor) || BOUNDARY-4 (lateral)] -> BOUNDARY-6 (F(S) wiring) -> [BOUNDARY-8 (status) || BOUNDARY-10 (E2E)]. Parallel tracks: BOUNDARY-7 (schema) -> BOUNDARY-5 (extractor). Tests: BOUNDARY-9 (unit+proptest) depends on T1+T2. Critical path: T1 -> T2 -> T6 -> T8 (4 serial steps). Maximum parallelism: T1 ready now, then T2||T3||T4||T7||T9 in parallel.; FAILURE MODE: Datalog type mismatch trap. Schema declares :task/status as ValueType::Keyword, so the store contains Value::Keyword(':task.status/open'). But natural Datalog syntax [?e :task/status \"open\"] matches Value::String('open'), which is a DIFFERENT type. Result: 0 matches when 634 tasks exist. The Rust API (resolve_task_status) correctly uses Value::Keyword pattern match. ONLY the Datalog query path is affected. Root cause: Datalog evaluator treats quoted literals as strings, colon-prefixed literals as keywords. User must write [?e :task/status :task.status/open] (keyword form). This is correct behavior per EAV type semantics, but the error is silent (returns 0 results, not an error). PROPOSED FIX: When a Datalog query returns 0 results AND the attribute has ValueType::Keyword in schema, emit a hint: 'Did you mean :task.status/open? (:task/status is a Keyword attribute, use :keyword syntax not \"string\")'. This is a UX issue, not a data integrity issue.; No Silent Boundary Skipping; Parameterized Boundary Checking; Session entity: :task/t-fc935f6e; ARCHITECTURAL DESIGN: Generalized Bilateral Loop — parameterized BoundaryCheck trait. F(S) becomes a weighted sum across ALL registered boundaries, not just spec↔impl. Each boundary is a pair of entity sets that should be aligned. The kernel (datom queries) is language-agnostic; only extractors (populating datoms) are language-specific. This follows the existing braid architecture. Boundaries: spec↔impl (existing), test↔reachable (lateral scan), schema↔usage, config↔runtime, branch↔merged. Adding a new boundary = one trait impl + one registration. The entire guidance→routing→correction pipeline works automatically for any boundary.; Boundary Divergence Honesty; DEEP INSIGHT: Dead-wiring is structurally identical to the HARVEST.md divergence problem that DDIS was built to solve. mod.rs is manually-maintained metadata that diverges from its source of truth (the filesystem). The maximally accretive fix is the same pattern: make the composition graph a PROJECTION of the implementation graph, not an independent artifact. For Rust: auto-generate mod.rs from filesystem (build.rs or automod crate). This is Prevention (layer 1), not Detection (layer 2). Detection (INV-REFLEXIVE-004 test) is the fallback; Prevention is the primary mechanism. The general principle: never independently maintain derived artifacts.; No Language-Specific Logic in Kernel Boundary Checks; Session entity: :task/t-b78da510; FAILURE MODE: Dead wiring — code exists, tests pass, but module is unreachable from main(). Root cause: Rust module system requires explicit pub mod declarations, and tests compile independently of module visibility. Formal property needed: INV-REFLEXIVE-004 — every tested pub fn must have a reachable path from main(). Three instances found this session: (1) diagnostics.rs missing pub mod in query/mod.rs, (2) spec_relevance_scan duplicate attempt, (3) KEFF tasks marked unimplemented when already done. Solution: structural test that verifies fs ≅ mod.rs for each module directory.; Generalized Boundary Framework over Hardcoded Bilateral; Session entity: :task/t-b5959bed; Session entity: :task/t-f9eb1f99; DESIGN DECISION: For dead-wiring prevention, the structural test (INV-REFLEXIVE-004) is the correct integration point, not automod or a new braid command. Reasoning: (1) The test runs in the existing cargo test pipeline which is already a mandatory quality gate. (2) Zero new dependencies — braid-kernel has no proc-macro deps and shouldn't add one for this. (3) Self-documenting — failure message explains the fix. (4) The test IS a projection — it derives the expected module list from the filesystem and compares to mod.rs, which is the correct DDIS pattern (projection over independent maintenance). (5) Compile-time prevention via automod would save ~0 seconds in practice (cargo test runs on every change). The three-layer guard is: Prevention = the test itself (catches at next cargo test, <1 min latency). Detection = clippy unreachable_pub (partial coverage). Correction = harvest methodology gap counter for unreachable tested functions.; Session entity: :task/t-fcb935b6; Session entity: :task/t-e59b8400; Session entity: :task/t-ffc41d7b; Session entity: :task/t-09fee3a8; Coherence Verification as Fundamental Problem\nSession entity: :task/t-5950fa0c; Session entity: :task/t-fd30188b; Session entity: :task/t-30c26830; Session entity: :task/t-55e59fdd" :op :assert}
